1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 {[pgndiagram]
Almost everyone played the classical Queen's Gambit's Declined back in those
days.  5 years later it would be tested extensively in Capablanca - Alekhine
match.} 7. Rc1 {A battle for tempo. White doesn't want to develop his light
squared bishop before Black takes on c4, as he would lose a tempo in the
proces.} c6 8. Qc2 Re8 9. Bd3 {White is first to give up} (9. h3 {Is a way of
continuing the struggle for tempo} h6 10. Bf4 c5 {But here Black can
contemplate striking in the center, as White has neglected his development.})
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 {[pgndiagram] Black's position is rather passive here. I
think that the classical gambit has disappeared from top level in the modern
era.} Nd5 11. Ne4 $6 {A move of a dubious quality} (11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Ne4 {
Leaves White with an edge}) 11... f5 $2 {[pgndiagram] But this is already a
big mistake. Black weakens his dark squares without any good reason} (11...
Qa5+ {Is the correct way of exploiting White's inaccuracy.} 12. Kf1 {The only
move} (12. Ned2 Nb4 13. Qc3 Bxg5 14. Nxg5 Qxg5 15. Qxb4 Qxg2 {Is horrible for
White}) 12... Bf8 {And Black is no worse, due to White's loss of castling right
}) 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Ned2 b5 {This weakens the c5 square as well and it was
probably better to avoid this move} (13... b6 {Is more reasonable} 14. O-O Bb7
{With passive, but defensible position}) 14. Bxd5 $1 {[pgndiagram] Great
judgement. White alters the pawn structure and gains complete control over the
c-file.} cxd5 15. O-O $6 {Probably not the most accurate.} (15. Qc6 {Would
paralyse entire Black Queenside} Rb8 16. O-O a5 17. Qc7 {And Black is dominated
}) 15... a5 16. Nb3 {[pgndiagram] Heading toward c5} (16. Qc6 {Is not that
effective any more due to} Ba6 {And Black is actually in good shape}) 16... a4
$6 {Not the best, chasing the kngiht where it wants to go anyway} (16... Ba6 {
Was the most resilient, although it seems to give a pawn away} 17. Nxa5 b4 18.
Rfe1 (18. Nc6 Qd6 19. Rfe1 Rec8) 18... Bb5 19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. Qxc6 Rxa2 {And the
position is suddenly unclear.}) 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. Qxc5 Qxc5 19. Rxc5 {The
exchanges have merely reinforced White's control of the position. c5 is rather
juicy and e5 just asks for a knight to be placed in it. Black is lagging in
development, and his bishop is extremely bad.} b4 20. Rfc1 Ba6 21. Ne5 Reb8 {
[pgndiagram] There is nothing Black can do in this position. Still, White
needs to deliver the knock - out blow} 22. f3 b3 23. a3 h6 24. Kf2 Kh7 25. h4 {
The plan is to advance the kingside pawns and bring the king up the board and
induce some weaknesses} Rf8 26. Kg3 Rfb8 27. Rc7 Bb5 (27... Rc8 {Is completely
hopeless} 28. Rxc8 Rxc8 29. Rxc8 Bxc8 30. Nd3 Kg6 31. Nc5 {And this endgame is
hopeless for Black}) 28. R1c5 Ba6 29. R5c6 Re8 30. Kf4 (30. Nd7 {Was winning
immediately as well} Kh8 31. Nc5 {And one of the weaknesses has to drop. c5 is
ideal for the knight}) 30... Kg8 (30... Bb5 {Was slightly more resilient} 31.
Rc5 Bf1 32. g3 Be2 33. Rf7 Rf8 34. Rxf8 Rxf8 {But still there is little hope
after White moves his rook and brings his knight to c5}) 31. h5 Bf1 32. g3 Ba6
(32... Bb5 $5) 33. Rf7 {[pgndiagram] The start of a beautiful combination} Kh7
(33... Kh8 {Was probably slightly more resilient, saving a tempo later on} 34.
Rcc7 Rg8 35. Ng6+ Kh7 36. Rce7 {But even so, Black would be busted}) 34. Rcc7
Rg8 35. Nd7 Kh8 36. Nf6 Rgf8 37. Rxg7 $1 {[pgndiagram] A very nice
"combination petite" as Capablanca would say, that crowns this positional
masterpiece.} Rxf6 38. Ke5 {And Black loses a rook, or gets mated. One of my
favourite Alekhine games, not because of the full blooded struggle, but
